{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17633592","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17633592"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:55:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:55:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17488"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17488","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17488"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10178"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71072"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10178","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10178"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17488"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56543"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4948"},{"type":"tags","id":"5392"},{"type":"tags","id":"5395"},{"type":"tags","id":"7799"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23836"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23885"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71072","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71072"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA research team conducts an observational study examining the relationship between coffee consumption and risk of heart disease. They find that people who drink more coffee have a higher rate of heart disease. However, they notice that coffee drinkers in their study also tend to be older than non-coffee drinkers.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the role of age in this study?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Age is a collider variable","Age is a confounding variable","Age is an effect modifier","Age is an intermediate variable","Age is the exposure variable"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn this study, \u003Cstrong\u003Eage is a confounding variable\u003C/strong\u003E because it independently influences both coffee consumption (the exposure) and heart disease risk (the outcome). This creates a spurious association between coffee and heart disease that may not represent a true causal relationship.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cul\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAge is an effect modifier\u003C/strong\u003E - Effect modification occurs when the relationship between exposure and outcome varies across levels of a third variable, which is not described here\u003C/li\u003E                \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAge is the exposure variable\u003C/strong\u003E - Coffee consumption is the exposure variable being studied, not age\u003C/li\u003E                \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAge is an intermediate variable\u003C/strong\u003E - An intermediate variable lies on the causal pathway between exposure and outcome. Age precedes both coffee consumption and heart disease, so cannot be intermediate\u003C/li\u003E                \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAge is a collider variable\u003C/strong\u003E - A collider is a variable that is influenced by both the exposure and outcome, which is not possible with age as it precedes both\u003C/li\u003E    \u003C/ul\u003E        \u003Cp\u003ETo address this confounding, researchers could use strategies such as age-matching, statistical adjustment for age in the analysis, or stratifying results by age groups.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Confounding occurs when a third variable influences both the exposure and outcome, leading to a spurious association.","Common strategies to control for confounding include randomisation, restriction, matching, and statistical adjustment.","Age is a classic confounding variable in many epidemiological studies as it often affects both exposure and disease risk."],"references":["Sullivan LM. Essentials of biostatistics in public health. 3rd ed. Burlington (MA): Jones \u0026 Bartlett Learning; 2018.","Dawson B, Trapp RG. Basic \u0026 clinical biostatistics. 4th ed. New York: McGraw-Hill; 2004."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56543"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17488"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56543","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56543"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-16T20:33:44+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-16T20:39:39+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10178"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71072"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGrou